    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-12">
      <h2>Implementation checklist for subscription box brands</h2>
      <p>Week one: audit all SMS opt-in sources, map them to Shopify customer records, configure quiet hours, and verify STOP/HELP handling. Do not launch automations until consent provenance is documented.</p>
      <p>Week two: launch one high-intent flow — usually cart recovery or back-in-stock for subscription box brands. Set strict exclusions and cap messages per customer per week.</p>
      <p>Week three: add replenishment or launch SMS only if product usage data supports it. Monthly recurring; skip behavior common; churn at month 3–4</p>
      <p>Week four: review cost per delivered message, opt-outs, and incremental orders. Adjust discount policy before scaling broadcasts.</p>
      <p>Ongoing: weekly consent and suppression review, monthly segment pruning, quarterly TCPA copy audit. SMS compounds through discipline, not volume.</p>
    </div>

    
      <h2>TCPA and quiet-hour checklist</h2>
      <p>Before scaling SMS for this store type, confirm express written consent for marketing texts, visible disclosure at every opt-in point, and documented quiet hours aligned to customer time zones. Audit monthly for popup copy drift, checkout checkbox changes, and flows that text after a purchase when email already confirmed delivery.</p>
      <p>Model weekly SMS caps per subscriber and cost per recovered order. If broadcasts spike opt-outs, pause and fix segmentation before increasing volume. Pair urgent texts with Sequenzy email sequences so education and proof do not compete with interrupts on the same day.</p>

    
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2>Cost-per-message worksheet for this category</h2>
      <p>Build a simple model: monthly SMS sends multiplied by platform per-message fee plus carrier fee, plus average discount cost per recovered order. Compare to full-price repeat purchase rate from the same segment. If recovery depends on escalating discounts, SMS may be training the wrong behavior even when dashboards show revenue.</p>
      <p>Document three tiers: conservative (one text per subscriber per week), moderate (two texts for high-intent only), aggressive (broadcast-heavy). Only the moderate tier should be default for most Shopify stores in this category — aggressive tiers belong behind explicit campaign approval.</p>
      <p>Sequenzy should own email education and winback sequencing; Postscript or Omnisend SMS should own cart recovery and launch urgency. Never send the same offer on both channels within twenty-four hours unless the customer explicitly opted into high-frequency updates.</p>
      <p>Run quarterly TCPA audits: popup copy, checkout checkbox language, keyword campaigns, and influencer landing pages must match actual automation content. Mismatches are the fastest path to opt-out spikes and complaint risk.</p>
    </div>

    
    <div class="prose-shopify card mt-8">
      <h2>Three SMS scenarios for this vertical</h2>
      <p><strong>Scenario A — High-intent recovery.</strong> Checkout-started SMS after email unopened, with quiet hours and no first-message discount. Postscript or Recart with Sequenzy email follow-up.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario B — Launch urgency.</strong> VIP SMS early access segmented by purchase history; suppress discount-only buyers. Cap at one launch text per week per subscriber.</p>
      <p><strong>Scenario C — Replenishment.</strong> SKU-specific timing from order date; skip if subscription active. Model cost per message against margin — consumables only where repeat window is predictable.</p>
    </div>
